    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"282835\">Jon Aytac</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/243068-ACT-2020/topic/July.207.3A.20Gioele.20Zardini.20et.20al.2E's.20talk/near/203135615\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>With regards to @James Fairbanks' question, Goldblatt gave a  modal S4 for spacetime</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"282835\">@Jon Aytac</span>  Interesting, do you have references?</p>",
        "id": 203139953,
        "sender_full_name": "Gioele Zardini",
        "timestamp": 1594146044
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>@Giole Zardini So, I looked at Goldblatt's paper and realized \"higher order modal S4 internal to the topos of presheaves on the Poincare Monoid\" is actually my own thought about building a higher order modal logic of spacetime (along the lines of our work here: <a href=\"http://www.cs.ox.ac.uk/ACT2019/preproceedings/Johnson-Freyd%20%20Jon%20Aytac%20and%20Geoffrey%20C.%20Hulette.pdf\">http://www.cs.ox.ac.uk/ACT2019/preproceedings/Johnson-Freyd%20%20Jon%20Aytac%20and%20Geoffrey%20C.%20Hulette.pdf</a>). Goldblatt's paper is here:  (<a href=\"https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1007/BF00370321.pdf\">https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1007/BF00370321.pdf</a>).  I had accidentally remembered my internal understanding of the thing as the thing.</p>",
        "id": 203141713,
        "sender_full_name": "Jon Aytac",
        "timestamp": 1594146954
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you very much, add on top of the reading list :)</p>",
